Generally, an increase in rates between 2010 (12.1% at least minimal to moderate sexual abuse) and 2018 (13.7% at least minimal to moderate sexual abuse) for the overall sample can be observed. While an increase in rates for females can be observed (2010: 14.9% at least minimal to moderate sexual abuse, 2016: 18.0% at least minimal to moderate sexual abuse, 2018: 18.2% at least minimal to moderate sexual abuse), the rates for male participants remained stable (2010: 9.2% at least minimal to moderate sexual abuse, 2016: 9.4% at least minimal to moderate sexual abuse, 2018: 8.9% at least minimal to moderate sexual abuse). The detailed rates are presented in Table 2
                        . χ2-tests only revealed differences in the rates of sexual abuse in female participants between 2010 and 2016 with negligible effect sizes (see Table 3
                        ). If controlled for multiple testing, e.g. with a Bonferroni-correction of the α-level, those differences did not reach a significance level.

Analyses of rates of sexual abuse by age group and gender, reveals varying rates in different age groups and for males and females (see Table 4
                        ). The major focus of the present study is on the age group of 18–29 year olds that represent the age group addressed in indicator 16.2.3 of the SDGs. The focus on this specific age group allows conclusions on more recent trends. The data show an increase in rates for this age group between 2016 and 2018. This increase is largely due to a sharp increase in rates among 18–29 year old females between 2016 and 2018, while the rate for males in the same period remains stable (Table 4 and Fig. 1
                        ). χ2- tests indicate statistical significant differences in rates with small effect sizes (see Tables Table 5A
                        5A, Table 5B
                        5B).
